def kfold(n, k=5):
    idx=list(range(n)); folds=[idx[i::k] for i in range(k)]
    for i in range(k):
        test=folds[i]; train=[j for j in idx if j not in test]
        yield train, test
for tr, te in kfold(10, 5):
    print('test:', te)
```

A single split's score depends on *which* points happened to land in the test set — high variance, especially on small data. K-fold rotates every point through the test set exactly once and averages the K scores, giving a lower-variance estimate plus a spread (std) that tells you how stable the model is.
